Read Saved Data

# Load Training data
data.train <- read.csv('TrainData_clf.csv')
data.test <- read.csv('TestData_clf.csv')
# sub data for svm
sub.idx.train <- sample(nrow(data.train), 10000)
sub.idx.test <- sample(nrow(data.test), 2000)
sub.x.train <- data.train[sub.idx.train, -ncol(data.train)]
sub.y.train <- as.factor(data.test[sub.idx.train, ncol(data.train)])
sub.x.test <- data.train[sub.idx.test, -ncol(data.test)]
sub.y.test <- as.factor(data.test[sub.idx.test, ncol(data.test)])
# whole data
X.train <- data.train[, -ncol(data.train)]
y.train <- as.factor(data.train[, ncol(data.train)])
X.test <- data.test[, -ncol(data.test)]
y.test <- as.factor(data.test[, ncol(data.test)])

Neural Network

library(tfestimators)
# return an input_fn for a given subset of data
response <- function() "ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL"
features <- function() setdiff(names(X.train), response())
  • construct feature columns
feature_columns <- feature_columns(
  column_numeric(features())
)
  • construct classifier
    • We use Adagrad optimizer and RELU activation function with no drop out rate after trying several combinations of hyperparameters. There are two layers in the network with 16 neurons and 8 neurous. The last layer is activated by logistic function by default for classification.
classifier <- dnn_classifier(
  feature_columns = feature_columns,
  hidden_units = c(16, 8),
  n_classes = 4,
  model_dir = 'dnn.md.2.layer.final'
)
  • construct input function
input_fn_delay <- function(data, num_epochs) {
  input_fn(data, 
           features = features(), 
           response = response(),
           batch_size = 128,
           num_epochs = num_epochs)
}

Training:

tfestimators::train(classifier, input_fn = input_fn_delay(data.train, num_epochs=2))

Predicting:

predictions <- predict(classifier, input_fn = input_fn_delay(data.test, num_epochs=1))

Confusion Matrix:

y.pred <- as.numeric(unlist(predictions$classes))
cm <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(y.pred), as.factor(y.test))
ggplot(data <- as.data.frame(cm$table), aes(x=Prediction, y=Reference, fill=Freq)) + geom_tile() + geom_text(aes(label = Freq))

From the confusion matrix, we can clearly see the predicted class.

Random Forest

Train and Tuning

library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.6-14
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
tuning.mtry <- c(2, 3, 4)
tuning.nodesize <- c(10, 4, 2)
mis.error <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = 3, ncol = 3)
j = 1
for (nodesize in tuning.nodesize) {
  i = 1
  for (mtry in tuning.mtry) {
    rf.fit =randomForest(X.train, 
                         as.factor(y.train), 
                         ntree = 500, 
                         mtry = mtry, 
                         nodesize = nodesize
    )
    y.pred = predict(rf.fit, X.test)
    y.pred = as.numeric(y.pred) - 1
    mis.error[i, j] = 1 - (sum(as.factor(y.pred) == y.test) / length(y.test))
    i = i + 1
    print(paste0("node size: ", nodesize, ", mtry: ", mtry))
  }
  j = j + 1
}
## [1] "node size: 10, mtry: 2"
## [1] "node size: 10, mtry: 3"
## [1] "node size: 10, mtry: 4"
## [1] "node size: 4, mtry: 2"
## [1] "node size: 4, mtry: 3"
## [1] "node size: 4, mtry: 4"
## [1] "node size: 2, mtry: 2"
## [1] "node size: 2, mtry: 3"
## [1] "node size: 2, mtry: 4"
matplot(tuning.mtry,
        mis.error,
        pch=19,
        col=c("red", "blue", "orange"),
        type="b",
        ylab="Misclassification Error",
        xlab="mtry number"
        )
legend("topright",
       legend=c("nodesize = 10", "nodesize = 4", "nodesize = 2"),
       pch=19,
       col=c("red", "blue", "orange"))

  • For the parameter tuning, I selected several values of mtry around 3 which is the squareroot of the number of variables in the dataset (by convention). From the plot, we can see that with the nodesize = 4 and mtry number = 4, we get the lowest classification error on the test dataset.

Best random forest model:

model = randomForest(X.train, as.factor(y.train), ntree = 500, mtry = 4, nodesize=4)

Predicting:

y.pred <- predict(model, X.test)
y.pred <- as.numeric(y.pred)-1

ggplot(data = as.data.frame(cm$table), aes(x=Prediction, y=Reference, fill=Freq)) + geom_tile() + geom_text(aes(label = Freq))

SVM

  • NOTE: During the project, we tried both hard-SVM and soft-SVM with various kernel methods. We found that SVM has a very poor performance for this task. After observing the figure generated by PCA, we conjecture it may due to the fact that SVM is not able to find a margin/boundary to separate the data. Training with svm is extremely time consuming. So we subsampled our dataset to about 10000 samples to get a feeling of this model. Note that this result may not be informable. The following parameters are among the several combinations we have tried for this project. We set the cost = 200 to avoid being too “soft”. If C is big, then lambda is small. Thus, weight will not be penalized, results in smaller margin.
